[In the past week there have been no newly reported cases in Pakistan, Nigeria, or the DR Congo. That being said, there have been positive environmental specimens in Pakistan (see the discussion below in section [2]), and there have been 2 non-paralytic cases of polio confirmed in Pakistan in the past week as well. It is too early to officially declare that transmission has been interrupted in any of these countries (Pakistan, Nigeria, and the DR Congo).

As mentioned in previous comments, these past 2 years have shown a reversal of type of poliovirus associated with paralytic disease, from a preponderance of WPVs to a preponderance of cVDPVs. It appears as though this year [2018] will end similar to last year [2017] with similar counts in both WPV- and cVDPV-associated paralytic disease, although there is a difference. Last year (2017) had cases of cVDPV reported by 2 countries (DR Congo and Syria), whereas this year (2018) there are 5 countries with active transmission of cVDPVs (Somalia, Nigeria, DR Congo, Niger, and Papua New Guinea).

For a map showing the locations of cases of WPV and cVDPV, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

